  "prompt": "What are your 10 favorite horror movies?",
  "response": "I don\u2019t have personal preferences or the ability to watch movies, but I can certainly recommend some popular and critically acclaimed horror films that many people enjoy. Here are ten horror movies, in no particular order:\n\n1. **\"The Exorcist\" (1973)** - Directed by William Friedkin, this classic film about demonic possession is often considered one of the scariest movies of all time.\n\n2. **\"Halloween\" (1978)** - John Carpenter\u2019s iconic slasher film introduces the infamous Michael Myers and is a staple of the horror genre.\n\n3. **\"Psycho\" (1960)** - Directed by Alfred Hitchcock, this thriller is famous for its suspenseful storytelling and iconic shower scene.\n\n4. **\"Get Out\" (2017)** - Jordan Peele\u2019s debut film blends horror and social commentary, earning critical acclaim and commercial success.\n\n5. **\"Hereditary\" (2018)** - Directed by Ari Aster, this film is praised for its unsettling atmosphere and Toni Collette\u2019s performance.\n\n6. **\"The Shining\" (1980)** - Stanley Kubrick\u2019s adaptation of Stephen King\u2019s novel is known for its haunting imagery and Jack Nicholson\u2019s memorable performance.\n\n7. **\"A Nightmare on Elm Street\" (1984)** - Wes Craven created one of horror\u2019s most iconic villains, Freddy Krueger, in this slasher classic.\n\n8. **\"The Thing\" (1982)** - Directed by John Carpenter, this film is celebrated for its special effects and intense, claustrophobic tension.\n\n9. **\"Rosemary's Baby\" (1968)** - Roman Polanski\u2019s psychological horror film explores themes of paranoia and motherhood.\n\n10. **\"The Babadook\" (2014)** - Jennifer Kent\u2019s film combines elements of psychological horror with a poignant examination of grief and motherhood.\n\nThese films have left a significant impact on the horror genre and continue to be beloved by audiences around the world.",
